>>18093607
Starting from the head, the eyes of the character indicate a slightly-turned head, but the snout went completely overboard and faced way too towards the side. The ears are just rudimentary rectangles and lack depth, yet you put much more effort into the eyes, which creates terrible contrast with the rest of the picture. It's uncanny and disturbing.

On the topic of depth, most of the dress(?) lacks value. It's just one big block of black, and the two while lines running down the torso is confusing and looked more like her waistline.

Everything below the head is a mess. The neck is unnaturally thick, and it gives off the impression that she has huge shoulders, further implied by the bulge of her dress and her arms. Breasts sag. Practice drawing drooping circles as opposed to melons shoved inside fabric.

You either used no references, or you used a reference but decided to draw from your mind as opposed to what you see. Don't do that. Make sure you draw the general structure of the body, and then add on the details. Either way, use a lot more references. It's not embarrassing to mimic a pose you saw in a fashion magazine because even the masters copied to learn. Plan out what the character structure looks like first, and then add details.

tl;dr If you really want to get into drawing. Look into figure drawing. It really helps you with improving anatomy and posing characters. Art books and online guides help a lot too, and there's many pdfs for you to access, free of charge.
